<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Meets U.S. Oil Businessman 12 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Meets U.S. Oil Businessman 12 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204132294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1303 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng said here today that the Chinese Government attached great 
importance to the development of oil and natural gas, both on 
land and offshore. 
  During a meeting with Kenneth Derr, chairman of the Chevron 
Corporation of the United States, Li said that China would like 
to cooperate with foreign petroleum companies, including 
Chevron, in this regard. 
  Li told the U.S. guest that since China began its 
exploitation of offshore oil fields in the 1970s, the industry 
had taken shape, and its prospect were very bright. 
  With development of the economy and improvement of people's 
living standards, China's demands for petroleum products would 
rise, Li said. Therefore, the country will accelerate the 
development of the industry. 
  He described the oil field in northwest China's Tarim Basin 
as one with great potential, and he extended a welcome to 
foreign oil companies to join in its development. 
  Li hoped that Chevron would be successful in the exploration 
for oil in East China Sea. 
  Chevron and China signed an agreement on the development of 
oil in that area last year. 
  Derr said that as one of the largest energy companies in the 
United States, Chevron had advantage in terms of capital and 
technology. The corporation has decided to strengthen the 
cooperation with China, in which it had confidence. 
  Derr and his party arrived here to participate in the 
strategic plan meeting from April 11 to 18, which is sponsored 
by Chevron Overseas Company. 
  Among those at today's meeting were Gan Ziyu, vice minister 
of the State National Planning Commission, and Wang Yan, general 
manager of the China National Offshore Oil Corporation. 

</TEXT>

