<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Cites Clinton on Bosnia Attacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Cites Clinton on Bosnia Attacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204201394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1955 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 12 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton said today he wouldn't rule out the possibility of 
expanding American-led air attacks against Serbs in Bosnia. 
  "If the U.N. forces there were put at risk, as they were in 
the shelling of Gorazde, we would offer close air support," 
Clinton told reporters at the White House. 
  "Every time we have been firm, though, in the end it's been 
a 
winner for the peace process, and I think it will be here," the 
President said. 
  It was reported that after two days of NATO air attacks on 
Serb troops, Gorazde's Muslim defenders were firing at Serbs in 
an attempt to provoke a response which could bring more NATO air 
strikes. 
  Clinton cautioned the Bosnian government forces "not to try 
to take advantage of this and violate the understandings 
themselves." 
  He stressed, "We have to be firm in our reaction to plain 
violations of the United Nations resolutions, and in what we 
said our policy would be." 
  "We have to be firm in pursuing the policy that we say we 
have," Clinton said, "it's our only chance for success." 
  Russia Monday [11 April] vigorously denounced NATO air 
attacks against Bosnian Serbs, warning that the move would lead 
to an escalation of war in Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
  Clinton said he had assured Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
that the United States had no interest in using NATO's airpower 
to affect the outcome of the war. 
  "But we do want to protect the U.N. mandate and we do want a 
negotiation there," he said, "and I think that is what we are 
going to get." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

