<H3> <TI>   Russia Denounces NATO Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Denounces NATO Air Strikes in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204142294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1342 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Russia today denounced 
again the NATO air strikes against Bosnian Serb positions near 
the town of Gorazde, urging an immediate end to the use of force 
in the former Yugoslav republic. 
  In a statement released here, Ivan Rybkin, speaker of the 
State Duma (lower house of the parliament), noted that the exact 
number of victims of NATO air strikes at Serb positions near the 
Bosnian town of Gorazde is still unknown and the military losses 
and the number of existence of civilian casualties have not been 
reported. 
  The statement said the air strike against Bosnian Serbs 
showed that NATO has easily ignored not only the view of Russia, 
but also the achieved agreements. 
  "We demand an immediate end to the unilateral, unsanctioned 
use of military force by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization 
and urge the parliaments of all the states of the world to 
actively contribute to the process of achieving a peaceful 
political settlement of the Yugoslav crisis," the statement said. 
  According to the ITAR-TASS NEWS AGENCY, the Duma speaker 
said 
on another occasion earlier today that NATO air strikes against 
the positions of Bosnian Serbs may be "an obstacle" to Russia's 
joining NATO's "partnership for peace" program. 

</TEXT>

