<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan's Hata Denies Coalition on Verge of Collapse </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Hata Denies Coalition on Verge of Collapse </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204143894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1424 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Japanese Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata today denied reports that the seven-party 
ruling coalition is on the verge of collapse over the selection 
of a new prime minister to succeed Morihiro Hosokawa who 
resigned last Friday [8 April]. 
  Hata, who is also leader of the Japan Renewal Party, the 
coalition's core force, told a press conference in Tokyo that 
the eight-month-old alliance has not broken up because meetings 
of the representatives from the ruling parties are still being 
held. 
  "It is true that various emotions are entangled," Hata 
said,"but if we go back to the starting point of why we 
established the coalition, I believe we can restore it." 
  The coalition is splitting into two camps over who should 
succeed the outgoing prime minister. 
  The camp led by the Renewal Party today rejected a call by 
Social Democratic Party Chairman Tomiichi Murayama to hold a 
meeting of all the seven parties' leaders to discuss the choice 
of Hosokawa's successor. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

