<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Portuguese Prime Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Portuguese Prime Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Supports Full Integration in GATT </H4>

<F P=102> LD1204211594 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
2000 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Cavaco Silva's economic pragmatism 
has come to the fore in the speech he has given in China: 
  [Begin Cavaco Silva recording] Portugal can operate as the 
door that will allow China into Europe. And in the same way 
that we see Macao as the springboard for Portuguese businesses 
into China, I believe Portugal can play a similar role in 
allowing Chinese businessmen into the European community. 
  I have also emphasized to the Chinese authorities our 
support 
for the full integration of China in the international economic, 
trade, and financial system. To this end we have been 
advocating and will continue to advocate China's full membership 
of the GATT system. [end recording] 
  Our special correspondent in Beijing, Feliciano Estevao, 
reports in connection with Cavaco Silva's speech: 
  [Begin Estevao recording] It is true that Cavaco Silva has 
given much to the Chinese authorities. For one thing he has 
volunteered his image and prestige in support of the cause of 
China's penetration of the EU's markets. As is known, in the 
aftermath of the Tiananmen events, China was banished from the 
political diaries of the EC countries. Second, Portugal 
supports the normalization of relations between the European 
Union and China. Cavaco Silva is of the view that there is no 
longer any justification for continuing to enforce sanctions, 
namely those banning visits by heads of state and monarchs to 
the People's Republic of China. Third, Cavaco Silva has 
unhesitantly advocated China's integration in the international 
economic and financial system, namely its membership of GATT. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

