<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujian Seeks To Attract Greater Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujian Seeks To Attract Greater Foreign Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204165794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1544 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fuzhou, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Eastern China's Fujian 
Province is trying to woo more investment from Hong Kong, Macao 
and Taiwan through improving its infrastructure facilities. 
  Wang Jianshuang, deputy-governor of the coastal province, 
told some delegates to the provincial people's congress and 
members of the provincial committee of the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference today that Fujian is to carry 
out preferential policies and upgrade its basic facilities and 
industries so that overseas investors can reap best economic 
returns in the province. 
  Continuous efforts will be made in the construction of the 
Xiamen special economic zone, the Fuzhou bonded zone and 
economic and technological development zones among others. 
  Investment in infrastructure sectors, including airports, 
railways, ports, electricity power plants, water supply and 
telecommunications, will be increased to 26.2 billion yuan, up 
20.4 percent compared with last year. 
  In addition, he said, the province will offer legal services 
for overseas investors and inquiry services on other issues of 
concern such as foreign exchange reforms and tax reforms in 
China. 
  He said that key sectors needing overseas investment include 
infrastructure construction projects, agriculture and the 
transformation of state-owned enterprises and finance, commerce, 
entertainment, information services and real estate. 
  The province is the home of many overseas Chinese. Figures 
from the provincial government show that there are eight million 
overseas Chinese who originally lived in the province. About 80 
percent of Taiwanese originated from Fujian. 
  By the end of March, a total of 13,543 foreign-funded 
enterprises were approved, with a contractual investment volume 
of 24.4 billion U.S. dollars. Actual investment reached 6.6 
billion U.S. dollars, about one-tenth of China's total overseas 
investment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

