<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Minister Arrives in Washington </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Trade Minister Arrives in Washington </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304063294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0605 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304063294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 12 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Foreign 
Trade and Economic Cooperation Minister Wu Yi arrived here this 
afternoon at the invitation of U.S. Secretary of Commerce Ronald 
H. Brown. 
  Wu is in Washington to co-chair with Brown the Eighth 
Session 
of the Sino-U.S. Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade to be 
held Wednesday and Thursday [13 and 14 April] and to conduct 
consultations on how to further expand bilateral trade and 
economic cooperation and other related issues. 
  A 37-member Chinese Government economic and trade delegation 
led by Wu took part in a Sino-U.S. trade and investment 
opportunity conference in Los Angeles before flying to 
Washington, D.C. and will attend a similar event in New York 
next week. 
  As she arrived at Washington's Dulles Airport Wu said that 
the "considerable progress" made in Sino-U.S. trade and economic 
ties had "brought enormous benefits" to both nations since the 
two countries established diplomatic relations. 
  However, she noted that bilateral trade and economic 
relations are still plagued by some problems and difficulties, 
whose solutions require the joint efforts of the governments, 
statesmen, business communities and people in all walks of life. 
  Wu was hopeful, she said, that the Sino-U.S. Seattle summit 
last November could be used as a starting point to maintain and 
boost high-level contact and exchanges between the two countries 
in all fields, strengthen mutual understanding, expand common 
interests, reduce and eliminate differences and bring bilateral 
relationships, including trade and economic aspects, back to 
healthy development. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

