<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Spokesman Defends Handling of Qiandao Incident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Spokesman Defends Handling of Qiandao Incident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304085494 Taipei CNA in English 0755 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Gabor Kurti] </F>
  [Text] Budapest, April 13 (CNA) -- Wu Jianmin, spokesman 
for Mainland China's Foreign Ministry, Tuesday [12 April] 
attempted to refute accusations that the Beijing government 
mishandled the March 31 Qiandao boat tragedy in which 24 Taiwan 
tourists died. 
  "We handled the affair in a very proper way. The accusations 
are not true," Wu told CNA Budapest. 
  Wu also said that criticism over the Mainland's human rights 
standards is unwarranted. 
  "It is not true that human rights are not respected," Wu 
said, noting China's success in feeding its people. "There is no 
more hunger in China." 
  Wu, visiting Budapest at the invitation of Hungarian Foreign 
Ministry Spokesman Janos Herman, added that Mainland China is 
focusing on developing basic shelter and care facilities for its 
people. 
  "Our priority is development. China's net population 
increase is 16 million people yearly, we have to care about 
them, create jobs and housing for them," he said. 

</TEXT>

