<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Postpones Taxing Stock Trading Gains </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Postpones Taxing Stock Trading Gains </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204120294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1124 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 12 (XINHUA) -- The central 
government has decided to shelve the plan for taxing gains from 
stock trading for at least two years, according to a senior 
Chinese tax official. 
  The move came a little more than three months after the 
enforcement of the revised tax laws on personal income, which 
stipulate that such gains should be taxed. 
  For quite some time, so rife were the rumors and 
speculations 
of a possible introduction of the tax that the stock market 
plummeted. 
  "The issue demands a whole set of principles and enforcement 
is rather complex," said vice-director of the State 
Administration of Taxation (SAT) Li Yonggui here today to the 
Beijing press. "Both the share-holding system and stock market 
are still in their infant stages. We need time to conduct 
research on how and when to introduce the tax. 
  "This year and the next, gains from stock transactions will 
not be taxed," assured Li. 
  Li said, however, whether or not to introduce the tax will 
depend on the research work and the real situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2770 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi071_n_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-071 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Exports Exceed Imports in First Quarter 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Exports Exceed Imports in First Quarter 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104142994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1413 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1104142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 11 (XINHUA) -- China's exports 
increased by half a percentage point more than its imports 
during the first three months of this year, the National Customs 
Office revealed here today. 
  This is the first time for more than 25 months that exports 
have grown faster than imports. 
  But the adverse trade balance in this first quarter still 
stood at 480 million U.S. dollars, while the total trade volume 
of 39.5 billion U.S. dollars showed an increase of 18.4 percent 
over the same period last year. 
  The customs department figures showed that exports for the 
quarter were worth 19.11 billion U.S. dollars (up 18.7 percent 
over 1993's first quarter) and imports totalled 20.39 billion 
U.S. dollars (up 18.2 percent). 
  Significant was that the growth rate of exports in the first 
quarter of 1993 was 7.4 percent, so this quarter's exports 
growth rate was 11.3 percentage points greater. In contrast, 
imports in the first three months of 1993 went up by 25.4 
percent, while this year that increase was 7.2 percentage points 
less steep. 
  According to some experts here, this phenomenon indicated 
that China's export capacity has recovered, while the excessive 
demand for imports has been effectively controlled, and China's 
foreign trade is becoming more stable and balanced. 
  It was learned that in the first three months of the year, 
China's exports of such products as clothes, textile products, 
shoes, toys, radio recorders and plastic products have increased 
steadily. 
  Meanwhile, the growth in imports of goods such as steel, 
refined oil, automobiles, aircraft, ships and textile machinery 
has slowed down, in some cases even dropped. However, imports 
of metal processing machinery and telephone switchboards have 
abruptly increased. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

