<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Labor Law To Be Enacted in 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    First Labor Law To Be Enacted in 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104113494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1104 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1104113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 11 (XINHUA) -- China's first labor 
law is now under formulation and is expected to be enacted this 
year. 
  Xue Zhaoyun, vice-chairwoman of the All-China Federation of 
Trade Unions (ACFTU), told a press conference here today that 
the draft labor law prepared by the Labor Ministry, the State 
Council's Legislative Affairs Bureau and ACFTU, has been 
approved by the State Council and has been submitted to the 
National People's Congress Standing Committee for deliberation. 
  If the law is passed, it will be China's first labor law, 
designed to standardize labor relations in an "all-round 
manner," Xue said. 
  The union leader noted that "brand new" labor relations are 
emerging in China to meet the needs of building a socialist 
market economy. And the law is expected to effectively protect 
the legitimate rights and interests of both employees and 
employer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2775 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi071_n_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-071 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chen Junsheng Notes Major Agricultural Tasks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chen Junsheng Notes Major Agricultural Tasks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204165894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1436 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 12 (XINHUA) -- State Councillor Chen 
Junsheng said recently that the major tasks of agriculture this 
year are to stabilize the output of grain, increase the output 
of cotton and enrich the vegetable basket. 
  He called on officials at all levels to actively mobilize 
departments in charge of funds, materials and technology to 
provide the farmers with good service throughout the process of 
production to strive for a good harvest of grain and cotton. 
  Chen, who has special responsibilities for agriculture, made 
these remarks during a survey tour of the provinces of Hebei, 
Shandong and Henan from April 6 to 12. 
  Chen pointed out that the three provinces are China's major 
producers of grain, cotton and vegetables, adding that the grain 
output of the provinces accounts for one fifth of the national 
total, while that of cotton accounts for half of the national 
total. 
  He stressed that at present, it is necessary to fight 
against 
the serious drought in Hebei and Henan Provinces and to increase 
the cotton-growing acreage. Attention should also be paid to 
the use of seeds from the best strains and to field management, 
including prevention and control of plant diseases and 
elimination of pests. 
  While concentrating on the production of grain and cotton, 
Chen Junsheng said, it is also important to provide more for the 
vegetable basket. Efforts should be made to use stalks to raise 
more cattle and other herbivorous animals and to grow more 
vegetables to enrich the supply of non-staple food. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2776 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi071_n_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
