<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Provinces, Regions To Increase Agricultural Output </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Provinces, Regions To Increase Agricultural Output </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104093094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0818 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1104093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 11 (XINHUA) -- Chinese localities 
have this year increased input into agricultural sector to boost 
the grain and cotton production growth, according to the 
PEOPLE'S DAILY [RENMIN RIBAO] today. 
  In Southwest China's Yunnan Province, the total capital 
investment in farm production has jumped to more than 2.5 
billion yuan this year. 
  The provincial fiscal budget for agriculture has been 
increased at an average annual rate of 23.2 percent since 1988, 
the highest in the country's provinces and autonomous regions. 
Last year's total investment was over 2.38 billion yuan. 
  To achieve good economic returns, the province has also 
restructured its farm products in a bid to achieve a total grain 
output of 11.25 billion kilograms this year. 
  The total grain-growing land has thus been expanded to 2.46 
million hectares by the end of March. 
  Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province has planned to put 
800 million yuan more in agriculture than last year while the 
total grain growing land is also expected to increase. 
  Over the past two years, the province has made efforts to 
improve 1.4 million ha of low-yield land and to reclaim nearly 
20,000 hectares of waste land. 
  In Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, land 
planted in cotton is expected to reach 740,000 ha, an increase 
of almost 140,000 ha over 1994. 
  The regional government has also framed a number of 
preferential policies to expand cotton growing land and has 
given priority to supplies needed by cotton growers. 

</TEXT>

