<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Chief Backs Germany's Bid for Permanent Council Seat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Chief Backs Germany's Bid for Permanent Council Seat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404015894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0126 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404015894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, April 13 (XINHUA) -- U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali said here today that he supports in 
principle Germany's request for a permanent seat in a reformed 
UN Security Council. 
  He made the statement at a press conference at the end of 
his 
two-day visit, his third to Germany. 
  Under the UN Charter, the decision on expanding the 15-seat 
council has to be taken by the UN General Assembly and he is not 
responsible for the issue, said Butrus-Ghali. 
  But the UN chief promised to appoint a German as an under- 
secretary-general. 
  He said he welcomes any role Germany can play in the UN. 
  The Security Council has five permanent members and some 
countries, including Germany and Japan, have tried to obtain 
permanent seats in the body. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2807 </DOCNO>
