<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., EU Reach Partial Accord on Government Procurement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., EU Reach Partial Accord on Government Procurement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404043794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0427 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404043794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Marrakesh, Morocco, April 13 (XINHUA) -- The United 
States and the European Union agreed today to open government 
contracts to competitive bids, except those of 
telecommunications, U.S. and EU trade representatives said here 
today. 
  Under the accord, European enterprises will have the right 
to 
compete for public bids in 39 U.S. states while American 
manufacturers of heavy-electrical equipment will be able to 
increase sales to state-owned utilities in Europe. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor and EU trade chief 
Leon Brittan made the announcement at a joint press conference 
in the city, where 120 ministers are meeting to sign the Uruguay 
round of trade accord reached last December under the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  Kantor said that the accord, to be signed Friday within the 
Uruguay round framework, will allow the two sides access to 
markets worth some 200 billion U.S. dollars. 
  But the public market of telecommunications in Europe, 
coveted by U.S. firms, still remains to be discussed here later. 
  Kantor and Brittan had met several times outside the 
ministerial meeting of GATT, which opened Tuesday in this 
Moroccan city and will last till Friday. 

</TEXT>

